The test should be parametrized with these values instead. 

@skipif_atcmd_disabled("SMSWAKEWIDTH")
@at_unlock_level_2
@pytest.mark.parametrize("good_values", ["1", "100", "5000", "65535"])
def QTI_INT_AT_SMSWAKEWIDTH_0000(target, helpers):

Then we don't need to have the for loop.

This should be a separate test. Test should be simple and do one action at a time so that when it fails, the failure is obvious. 

This test would be similar to above and use the parametrize decorator, but provide bad values. 

@skipif_atcmd_disabled("SMSWAKEWIDTH")
@at_unlock_level_2
@pytest.mark.parametrize("bad_values", ["0", "0000000000", "65536","65539", "10000000", "abcd", "-1", ""])
def QTI_INT_AT_SMSWAKEWIDTH_0001(target, helpers):
   target.run_at_cmd("AT!SMSWAKEWIDTH="+i, 1, [r"ERROR"])

This integration is already present so we should update the code. Although it can't know if "50" is supported but we can at least only run this test case if AT+KSIMSEL is enabled. 

To do this, add the following line above line 36. 

  @skipif_atcmd_disabled("AT+KSIMSEL")

From my comment in the oem/integrations PR. This would be more readable if it was 

  @skipif_atcmd_disabled("ATI", "AT+GMR", "AT+GMM")
  def QTI_INT_AT_ATI_0000(target, non_network_tests_setup_teardown, ati_fields):

The description would be enough to understand what it did and the comment above it would not be needed.

And in this case two decorators would be used. 

  @skipif_atcmd_disabled("ATI")
  @skipif_product_blacklisted("RC76", "EM91")
  def QTI_INT_AT_ATI8_0000(target, non_network_tests_setup_teardown):

This method is clear but only if we keep the decorators to a minimal. Two should be fine but if we need more then it can get messy.

Python has a very handy feature in that it supports the else clause in for-loops. You can update the code so that you do not need to check the i == (num_attemps-1)

  for i in range(num_attempts):
     ...
  else:
     # Exhausted all attempts
     pytest.fail("eSIM not set to active after %d retries" % (num_attempts))
